<article>
    <h1>Cough&#xAD;ing amid Covid-19: Why you must wear a mask</h1>
    <h2>Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore re&#xAD;searchers have de&#xAD;vel&#xAD;oped a su&#xAD;per&#xAD;com&#xAD;puter sim&#xAD;u&#xAD;la&#xAD;tion that shows how droplets fly when some&#xAD;one coughs with&#xAD;out a mask. Ti&#xAD;mothy Goh explains:</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-09"><time>2020-11-09</time></a>
        - <span>THE BIG STORY</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>How far can a cough droplet fly ?</p>
    <p>The dis­per­sion of droplets be­tween two peo­ple stand­ing 1m apart:</p>
    <p>With­out a face mask</p>
    <p>Re­searchers found that 100-mi­crome­tre cough droplets — the av­er­age size for such droplets — can travel up to 6.6m at a wind speed of 2m/s, Sin­ga­pore’s av­er­age wind speed. One mi­crome­tre is a mil­lionth of a me­tre. Droplets can fly even far­ther un­der dry con­di­tions.</p>
    <p>With a face mask</p>
    <p>When a mask is worn prop­erly, few to no droplets are re­leased into the at­mos­phere, ac­cord­ing to sci­en­tists here who used laser beams and a spe­cial cam­era to observe the droplets.</p>
    <p>De­tailed air­flow pat­terns be­tween two peo­ple</p>
    <p>• Re­cir­cu­lat­ing air­flows can be seen both in the front of the cougher and at the back of the other per­son. This may al­ter droplets’ tra­jec­to­ries and their fi­nal des­ti­na­tion.</p>
    <p>• Smaller droplets set­tle slowly and may be trapped in these re­cir­cu­lat­ing air­flows. This makes it dif­fi­cult to pre­dict the tra­jec­tory of cough droplets, and high­lights the need for wear­ing a mask, good per­sonal hy­giene, and keep­ing a well-ven­ti­lated en­vi­ron­ment.</p>

